    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars when food is cooked, resulting in new compounds with distinct flavors, colors, and aromas. In the case of bread crust browning, the reaction occurs between the proteins (amino acids) in the flour and the sugars, led by heat. This process typically begins around 140°C (284°F) to 150°C (302°F), with the most intense browning occurring between 150°C to 200°C (302°F to 392°F). At these temperatures, the proteins denature, creating a sticky surface that caramelizes and browns as it meets oxygen.",
      "source": "target",
